    <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">Chapter 3: The Editor UI - Complete Walkthrough</h2>

    <h3>The Canvas Overview</h3>
    <p>When we open n8n, we are greeted by an infinite grid dotted with nodes. The canvas is where we visually
        program our automation. Think of it as a spatial IDE where functions (Nodes) are visually linked by data flow
        (Connections).</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Nodes:</strong> The building blocks. A node represents a single operation-like receiving a webhook,
            fetching a Postgres row, or running a snippet of JavaScript.</li>
        <li><strong>Connections (The Wires):</strong> The lines connecting the right side (output) of one node to the
            left side (input) of another. They dictate the execution path.</li>
        <li><strong>Execution Paths:</strong> n8n runs nodes sequentially from left to right. If a node outputs multiple
            "items" (like 5 rows from a database), the next node runs 5 times automatically-once for each item.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Adding and Connecting Nodes</h3>
    <p>To add a node, click the large <code>+</code> button or right-click anywhere on the canvas. A search panel will
        appear allowing us to search for integrations (like Slack, GitHub, HTTP Request) or logical operations (like
        Switch, IF, Loop).</p>

    <p>To connect them, click and drag the small grey dot on the right side of our source node to the left side of our
        destination node. To delete a connection, hover over the wire and click the trash can icon.</p>

    <div class="usage-box">
        <strong>Developer Tip:</strong> We can branch executions easily. If we drag the output of Node A to both Node
        B and Node C, n8n will run Node B and Node C in parallel when Node A finishes.
    </div>

    <h3>The Node Panel Deep Dive</h3>
    <p>Double-clicking any node opens its configuration panel on the right. This panel is split into three crucial tabs:
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>Parameters:</strong> The core logic. This is where we configure the API endpoint, specify the
            database query, or write the JavaScript code. For app nodes, this is where we map fields securely using
            expressions.</li>
        <li><strong>Settings:</strong> Metadata for the execution. Here we can configure what happens if the node fails
            (<code>Continue On Fail</code>), if the node should execute once or per-item, and setup automatic retry
            logic (e.g., <code>Retry on Fail: 3 times</code>).</li>
        <li><strong>Notes:</strong> Plain text documentation. Always leave notes explaining <em>why</em> a node exists,
            perfectly matching the concept of code comments.</li>
    </ol>

