    <h3>The Expression Editor: <code>{{ }}</code> Syntax</h3>
    <p>We cannot hardcode everything. When we want Node B to dynamically use data generated by Node A (e.g., Node A
        fetches a user ID, Node B updates that user in a database), we use <strong>Expressions</strong>.</p>

    <p>n8n's expression syntax uses double curly braces: <code>{{ }}</code>. Anything inside the braces evaluates as
        pure JavaScript.</p>

    <pre><code class="language-javascript">// Accessing the output of the current item
{{ $json.email }}

// String interpolation using JS template literals
{{ `Hello ${$json.firstName}, your ID is ${$json.id}` }}

// Accessing data from a specific previous node
{{ $('Get User Data').item.json.email }}

// Running native JS methods
{{ $json.timestamp.split('T')[0] }}</code></pre>

    <div class="mistake-box">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> n8n evaluates the expression per <em>Item</em>. If the previous node outputs 10
        items, the expression <code>{{ $json.email }}</code> will run 10 times, dynamically resolving to a different
        email each time. Don't try to loop over <code>$json</code> manually using <code>.map()</code> unless we
        specifically need to process the entire batch at once.
    </div>

    <h3>Pinning Data for Testing</h3>
    <p>A massive pain point in automation is building workflows that rely on external webhooks. If we are building a
        Stripe integration, we don't want to make an actual purchase every time we test a node.</p>

    <p>n8n solves this with <strong>Pinned Data</strong>. We can trigger the webhook once, click the "Pin" icon on the
        node's output, and n8n will freeze that JSON payload. Every time we click "Test Workflow," n8n will pretend the
        webhook just fired with the pinned data, letting us build the rest of the workflow offline and
        instantaneously.</p>

    <h3>Workflow Settings</h3>
    <p>By clicking the gear icon in the toolbar, we access the global Workflow Settings. These variables override
        system defaults for this specific automation:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Error Workflow:</strong> We can specify a completely separate "Error Handler" workflow. If
            <em>any</em> node in the current workflow fails, n8n halts execution and passes the error trace to the Error
            Workflow (which could send a Slack alert or PageDuty ping).
        </li>
        <li><strong>Timezone:</strong> Overrides the <code>GENERIC_TIMEZONE</code> env variable. Crucial if a specific
            workflow handles localized cron jobs.</li>
        <li><strong>Execution Timeout:</strong> By default, workflows run until they finish. If we have an HTTP node
            hitting a frozen server, our workflow might hang indefinitely. Set a max timeout (e.g., 5 minutes) to
            forcefully kill hanging logic.</li>
    </ul>

